Later years (1990-2002)[edit]
In her final years, Saint Phalle was afflicted with emphysema,[5] asthma,[5] and severe arthritis,[6][13] which a number of commentators attributed to exposure to fumes and petrochemicals from materials used in her artworks.[5][17][6][13][61][28] Despite these handicaps, she launched into exploring new venues, new technologies, and new art media.
Throughout her career, Saint Phalle was outspoken in addressing important political and cultural issues of the time.[62][8] Her Tirs series and assemblages reflected the violence of the early 1960s Algerian War for independence from France, and asserted her rebellion as part of second-wave feminism.[1][27] Her enormous, curvaceous Nanas celebrated the fecund female form, featuring large breasts and buttocks, splayed limbs, joyous dance postures, and often, black skin.[46][63] She was one of the earliest artistic champions of AIDS awareness,[46] creating artworks and a widely-distributed book.[56] Shortly before her death, she exhibited drawings critical of the George W Bush administration.[46][64] In addition to her artworks, she wrote extensively in both French and in English, and granted numerous interviews; much of this material is collected in her archives.[65]
In 1989, Ricardo Menon, Saint Phalle's former assistant, died of AIDS.[10] She created a large mosaic cat, Chat de Ricardo, to serve as his cemetery headstone in Montparnasse Cemetery, Paris, France.[66] A second copy of the Chat de Ricardo is located in the Tarot Garden in Tuscany, where he had worked with her for many years.[59] In 1990, Saint Phalle completed Skull (Meditation Room), a 5-metre (16 ft) tall room-sized skull-shaped enclosure surfaced in colorful mosaics and lined inside with mosaic mirrors, to memorialize the AIDS crisis.[20][10] She also used bronze for the first time, in a series of Egyptian gods and goddesses.[10]
In August 1991, Jean Tinguely died suddenly of a heart attack in Bern, Switzerland. They had separated years ago, but remained very close; the loss of her longtime collaborator and intimate friend affected Saint Phalle deeply. She was writing a memoir letter about their first meeting, when news of his death reached her.[15]:103
In his memory, Saint Phalle created her first kinetic sculptures, which she called Méta-Tinguelys.[67] With initial assistance from her friend Larry Rivers, she created a series of kinetic reliefs or moving paintings, called Tableaux Éclatés ("Shattered Paintings"), in homage to her late husband and colleague.[7][34][68] When a visitor approached, a photocell would trigger motors which caused elements of the paintings to separate.[7]
As her health deteriorated, she worked on creating the Museum Tinguely in Basel, Switzerland, as well as continuing work on her Tarot Garden. During this time, she became a good friend of the museum's architect Mario Botta, and she also engaged him to design the wall and entryway to her Tarot Garden.[48]
In 1994, Saint Phalle published her hand-illustrated and hand-colored memoirs Mon Secret (My Secret) in French, and revealed her childhood history of sexual abuse.[14][13][69] In 1999, she released Traces, an English-language autobiography, which she also illustrated. In 2006, Harry and Me: The Family Years; 1950 - 1960 was published (posthumously), consisting of her self-illustrated memoirs from the decade when she was married to Harry Mathews.
Saint Phalle moved from Paris to La Jolla, California in 1994 for health reasons.[67][17][48][18][15]:79 She set up a new studio, and produced sculptures which were covered with mirrors, glass, and polished stones, instead of paints.[67][48] In her new workspace, she started to explore novel technologies for designing and creating artwork.[10] She also became an active member of the San Diego arts scene, participating in fund-raisers and exhibitions there.[5]
In 1994, she designed a stamp for Swiss Post. with the message "Stop AIDS/Stop SIDA", for which she was awarded the Prix Caran d’Ache.[70][10] She also began a series of silkscreened works, which she called California Diary, featuring local fauna.[15]:64 She started a new series of Totem pillars of stacked human or animal figures and anatomical fragments.[15]:64
In 1994, she finally declared the collaborative sculpture Le Cyclop, started in 1969 by Tinguely and worked on by 15 artists, to be finished.[43] The President of France, François Mitterrand, opened the work to the general public in May.[43] To control vandalism, the installation was donated to the French state, which has taken responsibility for its safeguarding and maintenance. The massive structure is 22.5 metres (74 ft) tall, weighs 350 tonnes (350,000 kg), and is filled with custom-built artworks, including a giant rolling ball sculpture.[43] Many of the artworks are kinetic, endowing the installation with constant motion, and producing loud groaning and other mechanical noises.[43]
In October 1994, the Niki Museum, dedicated to telling the story of her life and artwork, was opened in Nasu, Japan.[10] However, the Niki Museum would later be forced to close in 2011.[71][72]
In 1994, Saint Phalle worked with Peter Schamoni in making a documentary film about her life story, Niki de Saint Phalle: Wer ist das Monster – Du oder ich? ("Who is the Monster, You or I?").[10][73] In 1995, the film was awarded the Bavarian Film Award for best documentary.[15]:110
In 1996, she began building Gila, a large dragon-shaped children's playhouse for a San Diego private residence. This project was her first use of computerized techniques to enlarge drawings into full-scale construction.[10]
In 1996, she supported the opening of the Museum Tinguely in Basel, by donating 55 major sculptures and over 100 graphic works by Tinguely, which constituted much of the core collection.[34][10] She also donated some of her and her husband's artwork to create L’Espace Jean Tinguely and Niki de Saint Phalle at the Musée d’art et d’histoire in Fribourg, Switzerland.[10]
In 1997, she designed snake chairs of wood with a mosaic inlay, made by Del Cover and Dave Carr.[34]
In 1998, she created a series of Black Heroes sculptures in honor of African-Americans who made major contributions to sports or jazz, including Miles Davis, Louis Armstrong, and Josephine Baker.[15]:65 She dedicated the series to her great-grandchildren, who are of mixed race.[10] With assistance from Marco Zitelli, she also completed her series of 23 large animals for the Noah's Ark sculptural park at the Jerusalem Biblical Zoo, in collaboration with architect Mario Botta.[74][10]
In 1999, she debuted a monumental statue of Buddha, a one-eyed contemplative figure seated in the lotus position. The figure is covered with glittering mosaic tiles, glass, mirrors, and polished stones, and was installed in a nature garden.[8]
On 17 November 2000 she became an honorary citizen of Hannover, Germany, and donated 300 pieces of her artwork to the Sprengel Museum located there. In 2000, the artist was awarded with the Praemium Imperiale award for sculpture by the Japan Art Association.[75] The award is considered to be the equivalent of the Nobel Prize in the world of art.[34]
In 2001, she gave 170 pieces to the Musée d'art moderne et d'art contemporain (MAMAC) in Nice, France, and donated other works to the Musée des Arts Décoratifs in Paris.[34] She also designed and built a 12-metre (39 ft) tall sculpture, Coming Together, for the Port of San Diego. The sculpture, part of her Skinnies series, consists of a colorful half female and a black-and-white half male face joined together, covered with mosaic and stones, and was dedicated in October.[34]
Saint Phalle endured intensive care hospitalization for 6 months[6] before dying of respiratory failure (caused by emphysema) at Scripps Memorial Hospital in La Jolla, on 21 May 2002.[5][18] She was attended by her first husband Harry Mathews, and their children.[15]:79[13]
Up until the end, she continued to design further developments for her Tarot Garden in Italy, including a maze, for which land was cleared and metal rods were installed.[48] Upon her death, all new developments in her garden were halted, as she had previously specified.[48]
Posthumously, the Grotto (2001-2003) was completed according to detailed instructions left by Saint Phalle. The permanent installation, in the Grosser Garten, Herrenhausen Gardens , Hannover, consisted of three rooms which were decorated on every surface with mirrors, glass, ceramics, and colored stones.[76]
Posthumously, Queen Califia's Magical Circle (2000-2003), a 120-foot (37 m) diameter sun-drenched sculpture garden designed by Saint Phalle, was opened in Escondido, California in October 2002. It is enclosed in a 400-foot (120 m) undulating wall topped with huge python-like snakes, and includes a maze and 10 large sculptures she designed, comprising the largest public collection of her work in the US.[77][6] The decorations include symbols and plaques referring to her earlier Tarot Garden.
